94
00:05:57,557 --> 00:06:00,892
narrator: plasma is a yellow-colored liquid component of blood   

95
00:06:00,894 --> 00:06:03,495
that holds blood cells in suspension.         

96
00:06:03,497 --> 00:06:07,499
it's 90% water and contains critical proteins.

97
00:06:07,501 --> 00:06:11,036
companies harvest these proteins
from donated plasma      

98
00:06:11,038 --> 00:06:15,307
to manufacture medical treatments.      

99
00:06:15,309 --> 00:06:18,510
proteins from human plasma are used to treat shock,    

100
00:06:18,512 --> 00:06:23,382
bleeding disorders, and immune deficiencies.    

101
00:06:23,384 --> 00:06:26,585
first, the plasma is separated from the blood cells      

102
00:06:26,587 --> 00:06:27,986
and placed in a freezer    

103
00:06:27,988 --> 00:06:31,056
at a temperature of minus-4 degrees fahrenheit. 

104
00:06:31,058 --> 00:06:35,327
this process preserves it until
scientists can test its quality.

105
00:06:35,329 --> 00:06:37,663
a computer monitors the temperature        

106
00:06:37,665 --> 00:06:40,165
and prints out measurements so the team can ensure     

107
00:06:40,167 --> 00:06:43,102
the plasma remains adequately frozen.       

108
00:06:45,339 --> 00:06:49,874
ready for production, the plasma
goes from a freezer to a cooler,

109
00:06:49,876 --> 00:06:52,945
and then a warming bath to thaw the outer layer.    

110
00:06:55,349 --> 00:07:01,020
a machine collects the bottles and moves them into slots.   

111
00:07:01,022 --> 00:07:04,290
a blade slices them open to release the plasma.     

112
00:07:04,292 --> 00:07:07,026
the outer layer of plasma has liquefied,         

113
00:07:07,028 --> 00:07:10,095
but the cores are still frozen.

114
00:07:10,097 --> 00:07:15,367
then the plasma travels forward
to a heated mixing tank.    

115
00:07:15,369 --> 00:07:18,037
the agitator and heat break up the chunks,          

116
00:07:18,039 --> 00:07:21,106
and the plasma becomes liquid. 

117
00:07:21,108 --> 00:07:24,843
transferred to other tanks, technicians expose the plasma 

118
00:07:24,845 --> 00:07:29,114
to conditions that cause the proteins to become insoluble. 

119
00:07:29,116 --> 00:07:31,316
they're pressed into slabs.  

120
00:07:31,318 --> 00:07:35,587
in this form, the proteins are known as precipitate.   

121
00:07:35,589 --> 00:07:37,589
a technician scrapes the precipitate        

122
00:07:37,591 --> 00:07:39,058
off the filter sheets     

123
00:07:39,060 --> 00:07:43,195
and into a plastic-lined container.           

124
00:07:43,197 --> 00:07:45,931
an automated system retrieves the filter sheets       

125
00:07:45,933 --> 00:07:47,799
and takes them through wash stations     

126
00:07:47,801 --> 00:07:50,869
to remove residual precipitate.

127
00:07:50,871 --> 00:07:52,404
once thoroughly washed,    

128
00:07:52,406 --> 00:07:55,341
the filter sheets are ready for the next filtration.    

129
00:07:57,812 --> 00:07:59,944
a technician breaks the protein chunks       

130
00:07:59,946 --> 00:08:03,348
into smaller pieces and bags them for freezing.  

131
00:08:03,350 --> 00:08:05,818
this protein is called albumin.

132
00:08:05,820 --> 00:08:09,954
albumin helps maintain and repair tissue growth.   

133
00:08:09,956 --> 00:08:14,960
next, technicians dissolve the albumin protein in water. 

134
00:08:14,962 --> 00:08:17,896
they remove the precipitate from the freezer        

135
00:08:17,898 --> 00:08:20,332
and pound the outside of the bag
to further reduce       

136
00:08:20,334 --> 00:08:22,501
the size of the pieces inside. 

137
00:08:24,972 --> 00:08:28,574
then the bags of precipitate are emptied into the mixer,  

138
00:08:28,576 --> 00:08:30,909
causing the particles to disperse.          

139
00:08:34,048 --> 00:08:35,914
over the next day and a half, 

140
00:08:35,916 --> 00:08:40,853
processing continues to purify and concentrate the albumin.  

141
00:08:40,855 --> 00:08:44,122
at the same time, glass bottles
enter into a chamber      

142
00:08:44,124 --> 00:08:47,725
with cameras to take pictures of each bottle.        

143
00:08:47,727 --> 00:08:50,528
a computer locates defective bottles       

144
00:08:50,530 --> 00:08:54,933
and signals a mechanism to knock them out of the line. 

145
00:08:54,935 --> 00:08:58,203
the bottles cycle through a washing machine,   

146
00:08:58,205 --> 00:09:00,639
and then a hot tunnel for sterilization.       

147
00:09:03,010 --> 00:09:05,877
they're now ready for the albumin protein.    

148
00:09:05,879 --> 00:09:08,881
needles inject the protein into the bottles,       

149
00:09:08,883 --> 00:09:11,350
filling eight bottles simultaneously.    

150
00:09:14,955 --> 00:09:18,824
a robotic arm inserts stoppers in the neck of the bottles.  

151
00:09:21,895 --> 00:09:27,299
then a machine installs aluminum seals with flip caps. 

152
00:09:27,301 --> 00:09:31,837
they crimp the seals around the necks for extra protection.

153
00:09:31,839 --> 00:09:34,439
technicians load racks of the bottled albumin     

154
00:09:34,441 --> 00:09:36,374
into a pasteurizer.      

155
00:09:36,376 --> 00:09:38,043
the chamber fills with water  

156
00:09:38,045 --> 00:09:40,845
heated to 140 degrees fahrenheit.          

157
00:09:40,847 --> 00:09:43,482
this kills any potential pathogens.      

158
00:09:46,253 --> 00:09:49,922
the glass vials slowly spin by a magnifying glass     

159
00:09:49,924 --> 00:09:52,791
as inspectors scrutinize them for cracks,  

160
00:09:52,793 --> 00:09:56,628
missing stoppers, broken seals,
and other defects.       

161
00:09:59,132 --> 00:10:03,202
a technician takes out any product with physical flaws.  

162
00:10:03,204 --> 00:10:05,937
as the remaining bottles continue down the line,    

163
00:10:05,939 --> 00:10:08,407
an inspector examines them again.      

164
00:10:08,409 --> 00:10:14,146
this time, visually checking the
volume of the albumin protein. 

165
00:10:14,148 --> 00:10:16,681
at the next station, labels unwind,         

166
00:10:16,683 --> 00:10:18,216
and a camera takes a picture  

167
00:10:18,218 --> 00:10:21,753
for a computer check of the batch information.   

168
00:10:21,755 --> 00:10:26,358
the computer confirms that   
what's on the label is accurate.

169
00:10:26,360 --> 00:10:29,895
next, specialists place a sample
in a petri dish        

170
00:10:29,897 --> 00:10:32,497
and incubate it for 14 days.  

171
00:10:32,499 --> 00:10:35,433
if there are unwanted micro-organisms in the batch, 

172
00:10:35,435 --> 00:10:36,301
they'll grow.         

173
00:10:36,303 --> 00:10:37,369
but if not,          

174
00:10:37,371 --> 00:10:40,172
the protein therapy is cleared for use.      

175
00:10:40,174 --> 00:10:44,443
this protein therapy is now ready for medical emergencies. 

176
00:10:52,586 --> 00:10:57,789
♪♪         

177
00:10:57,791 --> 00:11:01,193
pictures on 3-d cups have depth
and appear to move,      

178
00:11:01,195 --> 00:11:03,328
depending on the angle you view them.         

179
00:11:03,330 --> 00:11:04,997
it's a neat trick made possible

180
00:11:04,999 --> 00:11:08,200
by a technology known as lenticular printing. 

181
00:11:08,202 --> 00:11:12,403
a sheet of tiny plastic lenses 
is applied to interlaced images,

182
00:11:12,405 --> 00:11:15,707
creating a kind of graphic magic
to entertain you.       

183
00:11:19,746 --> 00:11:22,214
a 3-d cup fools the eye.    

184
00:11:22,216 --> 00:11:23,615
viewed from different angles, 

185
00:11:23,617 --> 00:11:26,218
the artwork seems to come to life.        

186
00:11:26,220 --> 00:11:28,720
it's all a carefully crafted illusion.       

187
00:11:30,757 --> 00:11:35,827
making 3-d cups starts with clear plastic pellets.  

188
00:11:35,829 --> 00:11:37,762
an extruder machine melts the pellets          

189
00:11:37,764 --> 00:11:40,365
to a semi-liquid consistency. 

190
00:11:40,367 --> 00:11:45,771
an engraving cylinder forms it 
into rows of tiny convex lenses.

191
00:11:45,773 --> 00:11:49,241
water-chilled cylinders cool the sheet of lenses.   

192
00:11:49,243 --> 00:11:51,243
this solidifies the plastic,  

193
00:11:51,245 --> 00:11:54,846
then a gauge measures the lenses' thickness.     

194
00:11:54,848 --> 00:11:58,817
a blower device dissipates static.       

195
00:11:58,819 --> 00:12:01,987
an ink jet printer prints information on the edge.    

196
00:12:01,989 --> 00:12:05,190
this indicates the optical resolution of the lenses,   

197
00:12:05,192 --> 00:12:08,794
the type of plastic, and the lot number.      

198
00:12:08,796 --> 00:12:13,732
then a rotary blade cuts the plastic into sheets. 

199
00:12:13,734 --> 00:12:16,200
the sheets land in a neat stack.

200
00:12:16,202 --> 00:12:21,939
♪♪         

201
00:12:21,941 --> 00:12:24,476
to confirm their size and alignment,         

202
00:12:24,478 --> 00:12:29,748
an inspector views them against
a pitch test pattern.     

203
00:12:29,750 --> 00:12:33,618
another inspector magnifies a sample 100 times       

204
00:12:33,620 --> 00:12:36,288
and measures the thickness of the lenses.         

205
00:12:36,290 --> 00:12:37,889
too thin or thick,       

206
00:12:37,891 --> 00:12:40,892
and the lens display won't focus.          

207
00:12:40,894 --> 00:12:43,495
with a lens strip clamped at both ends,         

208
00:12:43,497 --> 00:12:45,964
the machine pulls it from the top.         

209
00:12:45,966 --> 00:12:48,033
how far it stretches until it breaks        

210
00:12:48,035 --> 00:12:49,668
is a measure of its strength. 

211
00:12:52,840 --> 00:12:58,844
meanwhile, a team designs and edits scenes on a computer.

212
00:12:58,846 --> 00:13:00,645
designers copy the scene,   

213
00:13:00,647 --> 00:13:02,914
divide it into very narrow strips,      

214
00:13:02,916 --> 00:13:06,718
and then interlace the strips. 

215
00:13:06,720 --> 00:13:09,454
next, the strips are combined into a 2-dimensional,     

216
00:13:09,456 --> 00:13:11,189
digital file.         

217
00:13:13,660 --> 00:13:17,062
designers now run test copies known as proofs.        

218
00:13:17,064 --> 00:13:20,398
this process tests sheets of colored plastic film    

219
00:13:20,400 --> 00:13:22,668
which will serve as ink.    

220
00:13:22,670 --> 00:13:24,736
the technician layers the colored film        

221
00:13:24,738 --> 00:13:27,139
in a cartridge with muslin paper.       

222
00:13:29,810 --> 00:13:31,876
next, the cartridge is placed in the printer    

223
00:13:31,878 --> 00:13:33,745
which creates the proofs.   

224
00:13:36,817 --> 00:13:40,752
the designer transfers them to an illuminated work surface 

225
00:13:40,754 --> 00:13:44,556
and confirms that the images  
line up with the plastic lenses.

226
00:13:46,694 --> 00:13:48,560
once the print plates are made,

227
00:13:48,562 --> 00:13:51,830
an operator loads them into the printer.       

228
00:13:51,832 --> 00:13:54,899
a suctioning arm feeds the lenticular plastic sheets   

229
00:13:54,901 --> 00:13:58,236
into the printer, reverse-side up.        

230
00:13:58,238 --> 00:14:00,706
in this position, the images will be printed   

231
00:14:00,708 --> 00:14:04,710
on the smooth side of the plastic.        

232
00:14:04,712 --> 00:14:07,913
rotating cylinders transfer ink
from the printing plates    

233
00:14:07,915 --> 00:14:12,049
to the sheets, one color at a time.      

234
00:14:12,051 --> 00:14:14,853
this system prints several different 3-d cup images    

235
00:14:14,855 --> 00:14:17,456
on each lenticular plastic sheet.         

236
00:14:21,728 --> 00:14:26,664
the press ejects and stacks the printed sheets.      

237
00:14:26,666 --> 00:14:30,535
the 3-d-printed sheets now head into a laminator.   

238
00:14:30,537 --> 00:14:33,672
it applies a white film to the artwork.        

239
00:14:33,674 --> 00:14:35,874
this film will protect the 3-d images         

240
00:14:35,876 --> 00:14:40,011
during the cup-molding process.

241
00:14:40,013 --> 00:14:43,815
next, the sheets are cut into cup-sized labels,     

242
00:14:43,817 --> 00:14:45,817
placed on an illuminated table 

243
00:14:45,819 --> 00:14:48,553
and inspected for any visual flaws.     

244
00:14:50,757 --> 00:14:53,558
once approved, the designer clears the the labels     

245
00:14:53,560 --> 00:14:56,894
to be formed to plastic cups. 

246
00:14:56,896 --> 00:15:00,432
next, an operator loads the stacks of 3-d labels    

247
00:15:00,434 --> 00:15:03,568
into the cup-forming machine. 

248
00:15:03,570 --> 00:15:06,037
this machine will process four different labels     

249
00:15:06,039 --> 00:15:07,705
onto cups at once.       

250
00:15:07,707 --> 00:15:11,442
each with a different 3-d image.

251
00:15:11,444 --> 00:15:14,446
a robot with suction grippers picks up the labels      

252
00:15:14,448 --> 00:15:15,714
one at a time         

253
00:15:15,716 --> 00:15:20,452
and transfers them to cup-shaped mandrels.    

254
00:15:20,454 --> 00:15:24,456
the mandrel inserts the 3-d label into the mold of a cup. 

255
00:15:24,458 --> 00:15:27,459
molten polypropylene flows into the mold,         

256
00:15:27,461 --> 00:15:30,195
and as it solidifies and becomes a cup,       

257
00:15:30,197 --> 00:15:33,598
the 3-d label fuses to it together.     

258
00:15:33,600 --> 00:15:35,667
robots retrieve the 3-d cups  

259
00:15:35,669 --> 00:15:39,037
and stack them on their sides to await final inspection.   

260
00:15:41,675 --> 00:15:43,675
then they're packaged for shipment.         

261
00:15:46,880 --> 00:15:50,549
3-d cups are no ordinary beverage container.      

262
00:15:50,551 --> 00:15:53,084
rather, they're a fun visual experience       

263
00:15:53,086 --> 00:15:55,687
for any type of consumer.   

264
00:15:55,689 --> 00:15:58,156
♪♪         

265
00:16:05,565 --> 00:16:10,969
♪♪         

266
00:16:10,971 --> 00:16:14,506
narrator: commercial breweries not only bottle and can their beer,   

267
00:16:14,508 --> 00:16:17,442
they also ship it in kegs to distributors, bars,     

268
00:16:17,444 --> 00:16:20,044
and restaurants.        

269
00:16:20,046 --> 00:16:22,947
kegs are typically made of stainless steel --     

270
00:16:22,949 --> 00:16:25,717
a durable metal that doesn't produce oxides  

271
00:16:25,719 --> 00:16:28,320
that adversely affect the taste of the beer.     

272
00:16:30,924 --> 00:16:33,591
this beer keg is made from a food-grade steel    

273
00:16:33,593 --> 00:16:35,994
commonly used for cookware.  

274
00:16:35,996 --> 00:16:39,530
it's exceptionally durable   
and contains sufficient chromium

275
00:16:39,532 --> 00:16:42,667
and nickel to protect against corrosion.       

276
00:16:42,669 --> 00:16:45,270
first, a technician coats a circular piece        

277
00:16:45,272 --> 00:16:47,672
of stainless steel with lubricant.        

278
00:16:47,674 --> 00:16:49,607
then the steel is placed in a machine          

279
00:16:49,609 --> 00:16:51,576
called a deep draw press.   

280
00:16:55,282 --> 00:16:58,350
the press slowly draws the edges of the metal circle 

281
00:16:58,352 --> 00:17:00,485
upward for 90 seconds,     

282
00:17:00,487 --> 00:17:04,822
forming a cylinder with one opened and one closed end.   

283
00:17:04,824 --> 00:17:08,560
next, technicians place the cylinder in a trimming machine,

284
00:17:08,562 --> 00:17:11,095
which spins the cylinder against a blade.        

285
00:17:11,097 --> 00:17:13,831
the machine cuts off half an inch of excess metal  

286
00:17:13,833 --> 00:17:17,435
from the open end.       

287
00:17:17,437 --> 00:17:22,707
then the cylinder is flipped and placed in a punch press.  

288
00:17:22,709 --> 00:17:26,077
the press knocks out      
a 2-inch hole in the closed end.

289
00:17:30,249 --> 00:17:33,251
next, technicians put the cylinder on a fixture   

290
00:17:33,253 --> 00:17:36,988
and secure a stainless steel neck to the hole.    

291
00:17:36,990 --> 00:17:39,257
the neck is welded into place. 

292
00:17:39,259 --> 00:17:44,996
♪♪         

293
00:17:44,998 --> 00:17:49,734
this cylinder will form the bottom half of the keg.  

294
00:17:49,736 --> 00:17:51,803
technicians pair it with another cylinder        

295
00:17:51,805 --> 00:17:54,272
which will form the top half of the keg.    

296
00:17:54,274 --> 00:17:57,609
this cylinder has an open end and a closed end.       

297
00:17:57,611 --> 00:18:00,478
they align the two open ends in a welding fixture      

298
00:18:00,480 --> 00:18:03,848
and manually tack       
weld them together in six spots.

299
00:18:05,886 --> 00:18:09,153
they transfer the assembled keg
to an automated machine    

300
00:18:09,155 --> 00:18:11,890
which welds the tacked perimeter together.      

301
00:18:14,895 --> 00:18:18,896
this press punches four holes into a 2-millimeter-thick strip

302
00:18:18,898 --> 00:18:22,434
of stainless steel to imprint the name of the brewery.    

303
00:18:26,106 --> 00:18:28,773
next, a roll machine curves the strip.       

304
00:18:28,775 --> 00:18:35,980
♪♪         

305
00:18:35,982 --> 00:18:40,184
then a seam welder joins the ends to form a circle.   

306
00:18:40,186 --> 00:18:41,853
this circle will become the handle           

307
00:18:41,855 --> 00:18:44,889
on top of the keg, known as the chime.      

308
00:18:47,861 --> 00:18:51,529
a technician places the circle on the chime-forming machine  

309
00:18:51,531 --> 00:18:54,365
and brushes on some lubricant. 

310
00:18:54,367 --> 00:18:56,601
automated, hydraulically driven rollers         

311
00:18:56,603 --> 00:18:59,670
then form the chime in three stages.        

312
00:18:59,672 --> 00:19:07,345
♪♪         

313
00:19:07,347 --> 00:19:11,950
next, the chime is placed   
on a punch press with lubricant.

314
00:19:11,952 --> 00:19:15,219
the press then knocks out two handle holes.       

315
00:19:15,221 --> 00:19:22,961
♪♪         

316
00:19:22,963 --> 00:19:25,496
technicians place another chime
underneath the keg       

317
00:19:25,498 --> 00:19:27,699
with one on top of this machine,

318
00:19:27,701 --> 00:19:30,969
appropriately named the keg crusher.        

319
00:19:30,971 --> 00:19:35,507
the machine presses both chimes in place.     

320
00:19:35,509 --> 00:19:38,309
next, an automated lathe welder welds them    

321
00:19:38,311 --> 00:19:40,412
to the keg simultaneously.   

322
00:19:44,050 --> 00:19:49,453
the keg is put through a series of baths, then rinses.

323
00:19:49,455 --> 00:19:52,990
the acid removes the scorch marks left by the welding   

324
00:19:52,992 --> 00:19:55,794
and render the stainless steel food safe 

325
00:19:55,796 --> 00:19:58,062
by making it resistant to oxidation,         

326
00:19:58,064 --> 00:20:01,065
which causes corrosion.    

327
00:20:01,067 --> 00:20:03,334
the valve, which connects to the tapping system     

328
00:20:03,336 --> 00:20:04,935
that draws out the beer,    

329
00:20:04,937 --> 00:20:08,072
goes through the hole in the bottom cylinder.    

330
00:20:08,074 --> 00:20:10,742
this clip ring holds it in place.       

331
00:20:10,744 --> 00:20:13,945
pressed deep into the neck with this tool.        

332
00:20:13,947 --> 00:20:20,084
♪♪         

333
00:20:20,086 --> 00:20:22,821
every keg goes through quality control testing    

334
00:20:22,823 --> 00:20:24,889
before it leaves the factory. 

335
00:20:24,891 --> 00:20:28,893
this is a pressure test to ensure the keg doesn't leak.

336
00:20:28,895 --> 00:20:31,696
technicians pump in compressed air to three times       

337
00:20:31,698 --> 00:20:35,166
the pressure the keg would ever have to withstand.    

338
00:20:35,168 --> 00:20:38,503
then they spray the keg with a water-and-soap solution,

339
00:20:38,505 --> 00:20:40,238
checking for air bubbles,   

340
00:20:40,240 --> 00:20:42,340
which would indicate a pinhole leak.        

341
00:20:45,645 --> 00:20:47,779
then the finishing touch.   

342
00:20:47,781 --> 00:20:49,380
a silk screen machine prints  

343
00:20:49,382 --> 00:20:52,317
the brewery's identification onto the keg.  

344
00:20:56,122 --> 00:21:00,525
the keg goes into an oven for 45 seconds to cure the ink,

345
00:21:00,527 --> 00:21:03,194
which renders it wear-resistant.

346
00:21:03,196 --> 00:21:07,332
these beer kegs are designed to
withstand a lifetime of handling

347
00:21:07,334 --> 00:21:10,935
because they're transported back
and forth between the brewery 

348
00:21:10,937 --> 00:21:14,071
and the establishments filling the beer glasses.   

349
00:21:14,073 --> 00:21:16,107
♪♪         

